    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->
     <insight>
        <p>
            Income tax is a compulsory contribution deducted from an individual's earnings based on their income structure.
        </p>

        <p>
            A worker's net income is built from:
        </p>

        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> \text{Gross Income} = \amp\; \text{Basic Salary} + \text{Allowances} </mrow>
                <mrow> \text{Taxable Income} = \amp \; \text{Gross Income} - \text{Allowable Deductions} </mrow>
                <mrow> \text{Gross Tax} = \amp \; \text{Taxable Income} \times \text{Tax Rate} </mrow>
                <mrow> \text{Net Tax (PAYE)} = \amp \; \text{Gross Tax} - \text{Personal Relief} </mrow>
                <mrow> \text{Net Income} = \amp \; \text{Gross Income} - \text{PAYE} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>

        <p>
            The key idea is that taxation reduces take-home pay, but the system is structured to ensure fairness through allowances and reliefs.
        </p>
     </insight>


